After seven months of negotiations with the university and 25 days on strike, the part-time faculty have reached a tentative agreement with the university. At 10PM on December 10th, The New School accepted the part-time facultyâs bottom line on health insurance, enabling the union to accept the deal in good conscience. 

Facing a boycott of all New School events by world renowned performers, designers, and authors; a class action lawsuit being considered by 1500 parents; and an onslaught of bad press after attempting to hire scab replacements, the university administration at last saw fit to put the needs of students and teachers over their bottom line. An agreement having been reached, the part-time faculty have agreed to suspend the strike while membership votes on the agreement, and intend to return to the classroom on December 11th. 

Pivotal to the end of the strike was the decisive late November part-time faculty vote, wherein 95% of voting members turned down the universityâs insulting âlast, best, and finalâ offer on pay and health insurance. Following the vote, the university returned to the table and agreed to seek the aid of a federal mediator. 

The university was further moved to bargain fairly with the part-time faculty after the union filed an Unfair Labor Practice charge against them. This ULP has now been withdrawn by the union as part of the conditions of the new tentative agreement. 

While the part-time faculty are saddened that the universityâs intransigence at the bargaining table forced them to leave their classrooms and take to the picket line, they emerge from their work strong, organized, and eager to face the struggles ahead. This tentative agreement is only the beginning, and the part-time faculty will continue to take power back from The New Schoolâs top executives and place it back where it belongs: with the faculty, staff, and students, without whom the university could not function.
